'''Francis Marion Davidson''' (born [[November 30]], [[1931]] in [[Gatesville, Texas]], known by his nickname '''"Cotton" Davidson''', was an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[History of the Indianapolis Colts|Baltimore Colts]] (1954, 1957), and the [[American Football League]]'s [[History of the Kansas City Chiefs|Dallas Texans]] (1960-1962) and [[Oakland Raiders]] (1962-1968).  

Davidson attended [[Baylor University]], <ref name="Statistics"/> <ref name="Cotton">[http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=DAVIDCOT01 Cotton Davidson on Database Football]</ref> and was selected in the first round of the [[1954 NFL Draft]] by the Baltimore Colts. <ref name="Statistics">[http://profootballreference.com/players/DaviCo00.htm Cotton Davidon statistics on Pro Football Reference]</ref>

As well as playing quarterback, Davidson also played the position of [[placekicker]] and [[punter (football position)|punter]].<ref name="Cotton"/>  Davidson was the [[Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterbacks|first starting quarterback]] of the Dallas Texans football franchise. Davidson was selected to the [[American Football League All-Star Game]] twice<U+2014>in 1961 and in 1963.<ref name="Statistics"/>  He was awarded as the [[MVP]] of the [[American Football League All-Star Game|1961 AFL All-Star Game]] with the Texans.

In 1963, the Chiefs traded Davidson to the Oakland Raiders for the first overall selection in the [[1963 American Football League Draft]], which was used by the Chiefs to select future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Famer]] [[Buck Buchanan]].

